  "description": "Working with phase space",
  "body_html": "<p>I\u2019ve been thinking about how to reason about <em>state</em> in biological and physical systems. In classical mechanics, one way to describe dynamical systems is through the variables we can measure at a point in time.</p><p>For example, the measurable variables for a single particle are its position and velocity. If it\u2019s moving in one dimension, the position is a single number, and the velocity is a single number, for a total of two variables. </p><p><em>Phase space</em> is the space of where these state variables can live. </p><p>Take a pendulum. I can describe the system through the angle it makes with the vertical axis, and the velocity of this angle. If we plot the values against each other, and then let time pass, we can trace out the phase space of a pendulum and see some interesting shapes evolve. </p><p>In the case of a pendulum with no friction, we get a closed loop. The x axis is the angle, and the y axis is the angular velocity. The animation below shows how phase space is traced out as the system evolves. </p><div class=\"captioned-image-container\"><figure><a class=\"image-link image2 is-viewable-img\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!CttK!,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd4f17ed7-87e3-4887-8a0c-9cfe589fb11d_1200x600.gif\" data-component-name=\"Image2ToDOM\"><div class=\"image2-inset\"><picture><source type=\"image/webp\" srcset=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!CttK!,w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd4f17ed7-87e3-4887-8a0c-9cfe589fb11d_1200x600.gif 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!CttK!,w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd4f17ed7-87e3-4887-8a0c-9cfe589fb11d_1200x600.gif 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!