ass=\"pencraft pc-reset pencraft icon-container view-image\"><svg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" width=\"20\" height=\"20\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" class=\"lucide lucide-maximize2 lucide-maximize-2\"><polyline points=\"15 3 21 3 21 9\"></polyline><polyline points=\"9 21 3 21 3 15\"></polyline><line x1=\"21\" x2=\"14\" y1=\"3\" y2=\"10\"></line><line x1=\"3\" x2=\"10\" y1=\"21\" y2=\"14\"></line></svg></button></div></div></div></a><figcaption class=\"image-caption\">User:XaosBits at English Wikipedia, CC BY 2.5 &lt;https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.5&gt;, via Wikimedia Commons</figcaption></figure></div><p>Then, we have the questions of <em>dynamics</em>. If I start on a point in phase space, what path is subsequently traced out? </p><div class=\"captioned-image-container\"><figure><a class=\"image-link image2 is-viewable-img\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!aWtt!,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F79fad9dc-9f9f-4b82-b529-e36e17260647_1500x1050.png\" data-component-name=\"Image2ToDOM\"><div class=\"image2-inset\"><picture><source type=\"image/webp\" srcset=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!aWtt!,w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F79fad9dc-9f9f-4b82-b529-e36e17260647_1500x1050.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!aWtt!,w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F79fad9dc-9f9f-4b82-b529-e36e17260647_1500x1050.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!aWtt!,w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F79fad9dc-9f9f-4b82-b529-e36e17260647_1500x1050.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!aWtt!,w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F79fad9dc-9f9f-4b82-b529-e36e17260647_1500x1050.png 1456w\" sizes=\"100vw\"><img src=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!aWtt!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F79fad9dc-9f9f-4b82-b529-e36e17260647_1500x1050.png\" width=\"1456\" height=\"1019\" data-attrs=\"{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/79fad9dc-9f9f-4b82-b529-e36e17260647_1500x1050.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:1019,&quot;width&quot;:1456,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:74783,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/png&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:&quot;https://chillphysicsenjoyer.substack.com/i/193462223?img=https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F79fad9dc-9f9f-4b82-b529-e36e17260647_1500x1050.png&quot;,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false,&quot;align&quot;:null,&quot;offset&quot;:false}\" class=\"sizing-normal\" alt=\"\" srcset=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!aWtt!,w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F79fad9dc-9f9f-4b82-b529-e36e17260647_1500x1050.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!aWtt!,w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F79fad9dc-9f9f-4b82-b529-e36e17260647_1500x1050.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!aWtt!,w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F79fad9dc-9f9f-4b82-b529-e36e17260647_1500x1050.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!aWtt!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F79fad9dc-9f9f-4b82-b529-e36e17260647_1500x1050.png 1456w\" sizes=\"100vw\" loading=\"lazy\"></picture><div class=\"image-link-expand\"><div class=\"pencraft pc-display-flex pc-gap-8 pc-reset\"><button tabindex=\"0\" type=\"button\" class=\"pencraft pc-reset pencraft icon-container restack-image\"><svg role=\"img\" width=\"20\" height=\"20\" viewBox=\"0 0 20 20\" fill=\"none\" stroke-width=\"1.5\" stroke=\"var(--color-fg-primary)\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\"><g><title></title><path d=\"M2.53001 7.81595C3.49179 4.73911 6.43281 2.5 9.91173 2.5C13.1684 2.5 15.9537 4.46214 17.0852 7.23684L17.6179 8.67647M17.6179 8.67647L18.5002 4.26471M17.6179 8.67647L13.6473 6.91176M17.4995 12.1841C16.5378 15.2609 13.5967 17.5 10.1178 17.5C6.86118 17.5 4.07589 15.5379 2.94432 12.7632L2.41165 11.3235M2.41165 11.3235L1.5293 15.7353M2.41165 11.3235L6.38224 13.0882\"></path></g></svg></button><button tabindex=\"0\" type=\"button\" class=\"pencraft pc-reset pencraft icon-container view-image\"><svg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" width=\"20\" height=\"20\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" class=\"lucide lucide-maximize2 lucide-maximize-2\"><polyline points=\"15 3 21 3 21 9\"></polyline><polyline points=\"9 21 3 21 3 15\"></polyline><line x1=\"21\" x2=\"14\" y1=\"3\" y2=\"10\"></line><line x1=\"3\" x2=\"10\" y1=\"21\" y2=\"14\"></line></svg></button></div></div></div></a></figure></div><p>In high school, we use Newton\u2019s laws to calculate the equations of motion. To do this, we use Newton\u2019s laws to figure out what the acceleration will be once you solve for the forces. </p><p>But there is another way to do this, called the Hamiltonian method. This method tells you where a point in phase space will go to as time evolves. To do this, we first need to calculate the Hamiltonian of a physical system, which is the sum of its kinetic and potential energy as a function of its phase space variables. If we label momentum as <em>p</em>, and position as <em>q</em> the Hamiltonian is given by </p><div class=\"latex-rendered\" data-attrs=\"{&quot;persistentExpression&quot;:&quot;H(q, p) = T(p) + V(q)&quot;,&quot;id&quot;:&quot;JVUPGGSXPZ&quot;}\" data-component-name=\"LatexBlockToDOM\"></div><p>where T(p) is the kinetic energy and V(q) is the potential energy.</p><p>With this Hamiltonian, we can calculate how each state variable will evolve according to Hamilton\u2019s equations. The equations relate the time derivative of each state variable as a function of the Hamiltonian, and crucially gives us an avenue to see how the state of a system evolves. </p><div class=\"latex-rendered\" data-attrs=\"{&quot;persistentExpression&quot;:&quot;\\\\dot{q}_i = \\\\frac{\\\\partial H}{\\\\partial p_i}, \\\\quad \\\\dot{p}_i = -\\\\frac{\\\\partial H}{\\\\partial q_i}, \\\\quad i = 1, \\\\ldots, N&quot;,&quot;id&quot;:&quot;UFKQKTBAOB&quot;}\" data-component-name=\"LatexBlockToDOM\"></div><p>As an example, lets look at the motion of a spring. A spring\u2019s Hamiltonian is</p><div class=\"latex-rendered\" data-attrs=\"{&quot;persistentExpression&quot;:&quot;H = \\\\frac{p^2}{2m} + \\\\frac{1}{2}k q^2&quot;,&quot;id&quot;:&quot;AHFKNKKPMB&quot;}\" data-component-name=\"LatexBlockToDOM\"></div><p>where <em>m</em> is the mass, <em>k</em> is the spring constant, <em>q</em> is the displacement, and $p$ is the momentum. In this formulation, we treat position and momentum as its own variables, and then see what pops out. Hamilton\u2019s equations for the spring give us the following equations </p><div class=\"latex-rendered\" data-attrs=\"{&quot;persistentExpression&quot;:&quot;\\\\dot{q} = \\\\frac{p}{m}, \\\\quad \\\\dot{p} = -kq&quot;,&quot;id&quot;:&quot;QBHSMMBFBM&quot;}\" data-component-name=\"LatexBlockToDOM\"></div><p>Now if we treat both variables as a function of time, and then solve it, we get that the solution is </p><div class=\"latex-rendered\" data-attrs=\"{&quot;persistentExpression&quot;:&quot;q(t) = q_0 \\\\cos(\\\\omega t) + \\\\frac{p_0}{m\\\\omega} \\\\sin(\\\\omega t)q(t) = q_0 \\\\cos(\\\\omega t) + \\\\frac{p_0}{m\\\\omega} \\\\sin(\\\\omega t)&quot;,&quot;id&quot;:&quot;JFGSVIGKEV&quot;}\" data-component-name=\"LatexBlockToDOM\"></div><div class=\"latex-rendered\" data-attrs=\"{&quot;persistentExpression&quot;:&quot;p(t) = p_0 \\\\cos(\\\\omega t) - m\\\\omega q_0 \\\\sin(\\\\omega t)&quot;,&quot;id&quot;:&quot;FPJGOAXNJQ&quot;}\" data-component-name=\"LatexBlockToDOM\"></div><p>where omega = sqrt{k/m} is the natural frequency of the spring, and q_0 and p_0 are the initial displacement and momentum. Now, if we choose a point in phase space, we can let the equations play out and see what lines we trace. In the case of a spring, it traces out an ellipse. </p><div class=\"captioned-image-container\"><figure><a class=\"image-link image2 is-viewable-img\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!gfrZ!,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6d420c17-ad77-4f2e-875f-9e3902c028f9_1200x600.gif\" data-component-name=\"Image2ToDOM\"><div class=\"image2-inset\"><picture><source type=\"image/webp\" srcset=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!gfrZ!,w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6d420c17-ad77-4f2e-875f-9e3902c028f9_1200x600.gif 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!gfrZ!,w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6d420c17-ad77-4f2e-875f-9e3902c028f9_1200x600.gif 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!gfrZ!,w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6d420c17-ad77-4f2e-875f-9e3902c028f9_1200x600.gif 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!gfrZ!,w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6d420c17-ad77-4f2e-875f-9e3902c028f9_1200x600.gif 1456w\" sizes=\"100vw\"><img src=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!gfrZ!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6d420c17-ad77-4f2e-875f-9e3902c028f9_1200x600.gif\" width=\"1200\" height=\"600\" data-attrs=\"{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/6d420c17-ad77-4f2e-875f-9e3902c028f9_1200x600.gif&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:600,&quot;width&quot;:1200,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:3032433,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/gif&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:&quot;https://chillphysicsenjoyer.substack.com/i/193462223?img=https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6d420c17-ad77-4f2e-875f-9e3902c028f9_1200x600.gif&quot;,&quot;isProcessing&quot;:false,&quot;align&quot;:null,&quot;offset&quot;:false}\" class=\"sizing-normal\" alt=\"\" srcset=\"https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!gfrZ!,w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6d420c17-ad77-4f2e-875f-9e3902c028f9_1200x600.gif 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!gfrZ!,w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6d420c17-ad77-4f2e-875f-9e3902c028f9_1200x600.gif 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!gfrZ!,w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6d420c17-ad77-4f2e-875f-9e3902c028f9_1200x600.gif 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/$s_!gfrZ!,w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6d420c17-ad77-4f2e-875f-9e3902c028f9_1200x600.gif 1456w\" sizes=\"100vw\" loading=\"lazy\"></picture><div class=\"image-link-expand\"><div class=\"pencraft pc-display-flex pc-gap-8 pc-reset\"><button tabindex=\"0\" type=\"button\" class=\"pencraft pc-reset pencraft icon-container restack-image\"><svg role=\"img\" width=\"20\" height=\"20\" viewBox=\"0 0 20 20\" fill=\"none\" stroke-width=\"1.5\" stroke=\"var(--color-fg-primary)\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\"><g><title></title><path d=\"M2.53001 7.81595C3.49179 4.73911 6.43281 2.5 9.91173 2.5C13.1684 2.5 15.9537 4.46214 17.0852 7.23684L17.6179 8.67647M17.6179 8.67647L18.5002 4.26471M17.6179 8.67647L13.6473 6.91176M17.4995 12.1841C16.5378 15.2609 13.5967 17.5 10.1178 17.5C6.86118 17.5 4.07589 15.5379 2.94432 12.7632L2.41165 11.3235M2.41165 11.3235L1.5293 15.7353M2.41165 11.3235L6.38224 13.0882\"></path></g></svg></button><button tabindex=\"0\" type=\"button\" class=\"pencraft pc-reset pencraft icon-container view-image\"><svg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" width=\"20\" height=\"20\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2\" stroke-linecap=\"round\" stroke-linejoin=\"round\" class=\"lucide lucide-maximize2 lucide-maximize-2\"><polyline points=\"15 3 21 3 21 9\"></polyline><polyline points=\"9 21 3 21 3 15\"></polyline><line x1=\"21\" x2=\"14\" y1=\"3\" y2=\"10\"></line><line x1=\"3\" x2=\"10\" y1=\"21\" y2=\"14\"></line></svg></button></div></div></div></a></figure></div><p>There are also interesting modern treatments that use phase space to predict the dynamics of a system. One such way is the delayed embedding method, which is a way to \u2018learn\u2019 the phase space trajectory by taking many observations. You could also think about phase space in terms of any state you want. For example, in biological systems, these could be temperature, CO2 concentration, and oxygen concentration. </p>",
  "truncated_body_text": "I\u2019ve been thinking about how to reason about state in biological and physical systems. In classical mechanics, one way to describe dynamical systems is through the variables we can measure at a point in time.",
